  "theoryOfChange": "Charity: Water utilizes a monitoring and evaluation framework called the 'MAP Framework' to understand the impact of its funded projects, maximize effectiveness, and guide future funding. This framework involves collecting data across a range of water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) indicators. The MAP Framework includes two primary types of data collection: Annual Check-ins, which are household surveys conducted at the baseline and endline of a grant, and Post-Implementation Monitoring, a comprehensive assessment of past funded work performed every few years. The organization also outlines its strategic approach on its 'Our Approach' page, detailing its methodology for planning, selecting partners, implementing projects, and ensuring long-term sustainability. Furthermore, Charity: Water has 'Strategic Pillars' that reflect its vision, focusing on providing safe drinking water, working with local implementing partners, aiming for long-term sustainability, incorporating sanitation and hygiene activities, focusing on rural communities, and targeting areas of high need and low income for concentrated, multi-year efforts.",
